g comparison correctly computes edit distance between primary and fallback outputs and stores the metric.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The behavior has two parts. The edit distance computation is a pure function testable at Unit level. The 'stores the metric' part requires that the computed value is correctly persisted — this failure can only appear when the computation result is handed to the storage layer and the two modules interact (wrong field name, missing commit, type coercion error). REAL-INFRA: Storage is to a local SQLite database; an in-memory SQLite suffices. MOCK-HIDE: If the storage layer is mocked, any bug in the write path (wrong column, missing flush, serialization error) is invisible. The real storage layer (even in-memory SQLite) must be exercised. LLM-DEP: Edit distance is a deterministic algorithm; no model output involved. REJECTION-GATE for Unit: 'and stores the metric' cannot be verified without a real storage layer — storage correctness is part of the stated behavior.","test_description":"Supply two known strings with a known edit distance (e.g., 'cat' and 'cut' → distance 1). Call the quality tracking component with these strings as the primary and fallback outputs against an in-memory SQLite database. Assert (a) the returned or stored metric equals the expected edit distance, and (b) querying the database confirms the metric row was persisted with the correct value, source text reference, and timestamp.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When both translators are available, the service returns the primary translation and logs the quality comparison in the background.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is at the orchestration layer — the service must (a) select the primary output over the fallback and (b) trigger the background quality-logging job without blocking the response. These behaviors only emerge when the primary translator stub, fallback stub, and background job wiring are all active together. A unit test on any one component in isolation cannot catch a bug where the service returns the fallback result instead of the primary, or where it blocks on the background job. REAL-INFRA: Both translators can be stubbed with deterministic return values; the background job can be verified via a captured call or an in-memory log store. No real network or subprocess needed. MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing both translators with distinct, known return values is sufficient — the test assertion checks which value the service returns to the caller, not the quality of translation. LLM-DEP: The behavior is about routing (which output is returned) and background-job triggering, not about translation quality; deterministic stubs fully verify these properties. REJECTION-GATE for Agentic: the behavior description says 'returns the primary translation' — verifying which of two stub strings is returned does not require a real model.","test_description":"Wire the service with a stub primary translator returning a fixed string (e.g., 'PRIM_OUTPUT') and a stub fallback translator returning a different fixed string (e.g., 'FALL_OUTPUT'). Configure both stubs to succeed. Call the service and assert (a) the response body equals 'PRIM_OUTPUT', not 'FALL_OUTPUT', and (b) the background quality-comparison job was enqueued or invoked (captured via a spy on the background task scheduler). Optionally assert the job was not awaited synchronously by measuring response latency against a slow background stub.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.09,"Agentic":0.17,"Workflow":0.04}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9584,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creati